{
  "chain": [
    {
      "repo": "grafana/grafana",
      "path": "pkg/tsdb/loki/api.go",
      "symbol": "LokiAPI"
    },
    {
      "repo": "grafana/grafana",
      "path": "pkg/tsdb/loki/api.go",
      "symbol": "DataQuery"
    },
    {
      "repo": "grafana/grafana",
      "path": "pkg/tsdb/loki/api.go",
      "symbol": "makeDataRequest"
    },
    {
      "repo": "sg-benchmarks/grafana-loki",
      "path": "pkg/loghttp/query.go",
      "symbol": "ParseInstantQuery"
    }
  ],
  "text": "When Grafana executes a log query to a Loki datasource, the HTTP call chain flows as follows:\n\n1. **Grafana HTTP Client Setup (grafana/grafana:pkg/tsdb/loki/api.go)**: The `LokiAPI` struct (line 29) is the primary type that acts as an HTTP client for Loki queries. It wraps `*http.Client` and is initialized in `newLokiAPI` (line 42).\n\n2. **Query Execution (grafana/grafana:pkg/tsdb/loki/api.go:DataQuery)**: The `DataQuery` method (line 172) is the main entry point for executing queries. It calls `makeDataRequest` to construct the HTTP request, then executes it via `api.client.Do(req)` (line 181).\n\n3. **Request Construction (grafana/grafana:pkg/tsdb/loki/api.go:makeDataRequest)**: This function (line 46) builds the HTTP GET request with query parameters. For instant queries (detected at line 83), it sets the path to `/loki/api/v1/query` and includes query parameters like `query`, `time`, and `limit`.\n\n4. **Loki HTTP Parsing (sg-benchmarks/grafana-loki:pkg/loghttp/query.go:ParseInstantQuery)**: On the Loki side, the `ParseInstantQuery` function (line 418) parses the incoming HTTP request. It extracts parameters from the HTTP request (query string, timestamp, limit, direction, shards) and constructs an `InstantQuery` struct containing all the parsed query parameters.\n\nThis chain shows how Grafana's query request flows through its HTTP client layer and gets parsed on the Loki backend."
}

